Start with the [Transactional outbox](https://microservices.io/patterns/data/transactional-outbox.html) pattern—it’s the most important fundamental for understanding how systems talk to each other without losing data when a network blips or a database transaction fails.

Most people start with the "how" of sending messages, but the durable skill is learning how to maintain consistency when you don't have a single database to rule them all. The [Pattern: Saga](https://microservices.io/patterns/data/saga.html) covers how to manage these long-running business workflows across multiple services, specifically the trade-off between choreography (services reacting to events) and orchestration (a central controller).

If you want to go deeper into how state itself is stored, [Event Sourcing](https://martinfowler.com/eaaDev/EventSourcing.html) flips the model from "store the current state" to "store the history of changes." It’s powerful for audit trails and reconstructing past states, but it adds significant complexity, so it's worth reading Martin Fowler’s [Monolith First](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/MonolithFirst.html) as a pragmatic reality check before you decompose every system into events.

