```

Once you start firing events into the void, your biggest challenge won’t be the code—it’ll be figuring out where a message stopped and why.

At 10k events/min, SQS is the safer bet for availability and burst handling, but Postgres `SKIP LOCKED` is the right choice if you need atomic consistency between your database updates and your task enqueueing.

The risk with the Postgres approach at this scale is "DDOS-ing" your own database. As you add workers to handle a burst, the frantic pace of workers trying to lock rows can [cause the queue to spiral out of control](https://brandur.org/job-drain), especially if you have long-running transactions. [Celery Best Practices](https://denibertovic.com/posts/celery-best-practices/) warns that high-frequency polling can spike disk IO and take down your entire application alongside the queue.

SQS avoids the locking bottleneck entirely, but it forces you to deal with [at-least-once delivery semantics](https://www.rabbitmq.com/tutorials/tutorial-two-python). Since the queue and the database aren't in the same transaction, you'll eventually face "dual-write" failures where a job is enqueued but the DB transaction fails, or vice versa. This makes [idempotency keys](https://brandur.org/idempotency-keys) a requirement for your consumers rather than an optimization.

