```

If you need the transactional safety of Postgres but the scale of a dedicated broker, consider [transactionally staging jobs in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain) and using a separate "drain" process to move them into SQS in bulk.

Before you go all-in on SQS, decide how you'll handle the "invisible" failure mode: your database transaction commits, but the network call to SQS fails.

Start with the first half of [Designing Data-Intensive Applications](https://dataintensive.net/). It’s the most effective way to build a mental model of what’s happening "under the hood" of the systems you already use every day.

Chapters 3 and 7 are where you’ll find the deep dives into storage engines and transactions. You’ll learn how Write-Ahead Logging (WAL) ensures durability by turning random writes into sequential ones and how Multi-Version Concurrency Control (MVCC) allows readers and writers to coexist without locking the entire world. It’s less about memorizing specific database flags and more about understanding why these systems were designed this way in the first place.

To bridge the gap between that theory and your actual SQL queries, follow it up with [Use The Index, Luke!](https://use-the-index-luke.com/). It explains indexing from the ground up, focusing on the mechanics of B-Trees and how they satisfy—or fail to satisfy—complex lookups.

