```

Once you’ve internalized how a Write-Ahead Log works, you’ll start seeing its fingerprints in everything from filesystem journals to distributed consensus protocols.

Treat the agentic loop as a single distributed trace where each iteration and subsequent tool call is recorded as a nested span. By propagating the original request context into the loop, you keep the agent's work linked to the production trace that triggered it rather than letting it drift into disconnected logs.

Since an agent's core behavior is [running tools in a loop to achieve a goal](https://simonwillison.net/2025/Sep/30/designing-agentic-loops/), you should map every "turn" of that loop to a trace span and every individual tool execution to a child span. This structure allows you to [pinpoint exactly where slowdowns occur](https://docs.newrelic.com/docs/apm/new-relic-apm/getting-started/introduction-apm/)—revealing whether the agent is stuck in a recursive hallucination or if a specific tool is timing out. Use [OpenTelemetry](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/getting-started/) to standardize these spans so they carry through async boundaries and third-party API calls.

The real value of this instrumentation is the ability to [unify logs, metrics, and traces](https://betterstack.com/docs/logs/tracing/) in one view. When a loop goes runaway, you need to see the high-cardinality data—like the exact JSON payload passed to a tool—alongside the timing data to understand *why* the agent is looping. Standardizing on spans rather than just "print" debugging ensures you can observe these [inherently dangerous](https://simonwillison.net/2025/Sep/30/designing-agentic-loops/) behaviors in production without losing the thread of the original user session.

